<DOC><DOCNO> AP880812-0039 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 0349EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     08-12 0565</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,530</SECOND><HEAD>Independent Panel Proposed to Police House of Reps</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two congressman, saying they want to restorethe public's faith in Congress, have introduced legislation tocreate an independent panel to investigate alleged ethicsviolations in the House of Representatives.   Reps. Joseph DioGuardi, R-N.Y., and Barney Frank, D-Mass., alsoproposed creating the office of an independent inspector general toaudit financial matters of the House and its members.   ``What we're trying to deal with here is the perception thatcongressmen are not fulfilling their public trust,'' DioGuardi saidat a news conference Thursday.   He said the public ranks congressmen ``just below snake oilsalesmen'' when it comes to ethics.   Both congressmen stressed the conflicts inherent in the currentsystem, nder which House members police themselves through theCommittee on Standards of Official Conduct. That panel, composed ofan equal number of Republicans and Democrats, enforces the code ofconduct and recommends to the full House sanctions against memberswho violate the code.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Heat Wave Costs Americans a Cool $255 Million Extra in July</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Americans spent $4.3 billion on airconditioning in July, which the government says is more than aquarter-billion dollars more than usual for the month.   The hot month, which brought high temperatures and little rainto much of the nation, added some $255 million more to the nationalair conditioning bill than would be expected in a normal July, theNational Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration reported Thursday.   That averaged out to a July air conditioning bill of $104 forthe typical home, $6 more than normal.   Only the west south central states _ Texas, Louisiana, Arkansasand Oklahoma spent less on cooling than in a typical July. Thehighest increase were in the East North Central region _ includingthe Great Lakes States _ which showed an average bill $16 more thannormal.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>U.S. Official, Researcher Differ Over Response to Global Warming</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Reagan administration official says moreresearch is needed on the effects of the ``greenhouse effect,''even though a private weather researcher told Congress action isneeded soon to slow the global warming.   Donna Fitzpatrick, associate undersecretary of energy, told acongressional panel Thursday that ``scientific uncertainties mustbe reduced before we commit the nation's economic future to drasticand potentially misplaced policy responses.''   But climatologist Stephen Schneider told the Senate Energy andNatural Resources Committee the administration is expressing``political value judgments, not scientific opinions.''   ``We should not use platitudes about scientific uncertainty asan excuse for inaction,'' Schneider, who works at the NationalCenter for Atmospheric Research in Boulder, Colo., testified.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Top Federal Cancer Researcher Leaving For Private Job</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The director of the National Cancer Institute,Dr. Vincent T. DeVita Jr., is resigning his government post,reportedly to become chief physician at Memorial Sloan KetteringCancer Center in New York City.   Storm Whaley, press officer for the parent National Institutesof Health, said Thursday that DeVita was leaving government, butcould not confirm a report by The Washington Post that DeVita istaking the New York job.   The newspaper cited several sources, all unidentified, as sayingDeVita will replace Dr. Samuel Hellman at Sloan Kettering.   DeVita, 53, has been head of NCI since 1975 and his regarded asone of the nation's most influential figures in cancer research,particularly chemotherapy.